      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Carboxylic acids (RCO<sub>2</sub>H; p<i>K</i><sub>a</sub> ≈ 5) are approximately 10<sup>11</sup> times more acidic than alcohols (ROH; p<i>K</i><sub>a</sub> ≈ 16). In other words, a carboxylate ion (RCO<sub>2</sub><sup>−</sup>) is more stable than an alkoxide ion (RO<sup>−</sup>). Explain, using resonance.</p>",
